      • asFactory

        @NotNull
public static <IN,OUT> InvocationFactory<IN,OUT> asFactory(@NotNull
                                                                    Function<? super StreamChannel<IN,IN>,? extends StreamChannel<? super IN,? extends OUT>> function)
        Returns an invocation factory, whose invocation instances employ the stream channels, provided by the specified function, to process input data.
        The function should return a new instance each time it is called, starting from the passed one.
        Type Parameters:
        IN - the input data type.
        OUT - the output data type.
        Parameters:
        function - the function providing the stream channels.
        Returns:
        the invocation factory.

      • blend

        @NotNull
public static <OUT> ChannelsBuilder<? extends StreamChannel<OUT,OUT>> blend(@NotNull
                                                                                     Iterable<? extends Channel<?,? extends OUT>> channels)
        Returns a builder of streams blending the outputs coming from the specified channels.

        Note that the builder will successfully create only one stream channel instance, and that the passed channels will be bound as a result of the creation.
        Note also that the returned channel will be already closed.

        Type Parameters:
        OUT - the output data type.
        Parameters:
        channels - the iterable of channels.
        Returns:
        the stream channel builder.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified iterable is empty.
        NullPointerException - if the specified iterable is null or contains a null object.
        See Also:
        Channels.blend(Iterable)

      • distribute

        @NotNull
public static <IN> ChannelsBuilder<? extends Channel<List<? extends IN>,?>> distribute(@Nullable
                                                                                                IN placeholder,
                                                                                                @NotNull
                                                                                                Channel<?,?>... channels)
        Returns a builder of channels distributing the input data among the specified ones. If the list of data is smaller than the specified number of channels, the remaining ones will be fed with the specified placeholder instance. While, if the list of data exceeds the number of channels, the invocation will be aborted.

        Note that the builder will successfully create several channel instances.

        Type Parameters:
        IN - the input data type.
        Parameters:
        placeholder - the placeholder instance.
        channels - the array of channels.
        Returns:
        the channel builder.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified array is empty.
        NullPointerException - if the specified array is null or contains a null object.

        @NotNull
public static <OUT> ChannelsBuilder<? extends StreamChannel<List<? extends OUT>,List<? extends OUT>>> join(@NotNull
                                                                                                                    Iterable<? extends Channel<?,? extends OUT>> channels)
        Returns a builder of stream channels joining the data coming from the specified ones.
        An output will be generated only when at least one result is available for each channel.

        Note that the builder will successfully create only one stream channel instance, and that the passed channels will be bound as a result of the creation.
        Note also that the returned channel will be already closed.

      • join

        @NotNull
public static <OUT> ChannelsBuilder<? extends StreamChannel<List<? extends OUT>,List<? extends OUT>>> join(@Nullable
                                                                                                                    OUT placeholder,
                                                                                                                    @NotNull
                                                                                                                    Iterable<? extends Channel<?,? extends OUT>> channels)
        Returns a builder of stream channels joining the data coming from the specified ones.
        An output will be generated only when at least one result is available for each channel. Moreover, when all the channels are closed, the remaining outputs will be returned by filling the gaps with the specified placeholder instance, so that the generated list of data will always have the same size of the channel list.

        Note that the builder will successfully create only one stream channel instance, and that the passed channels will be bound as a result of the creation.
        Note also that the returned channel will be already closed.

        Type Parameters:
        OUT - the output data type.
        Parameters:
        placeholder - the placeholder instance.
        channels - the iterable of channels.
        Returns:
        the stream channel builder.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified iterable is empty.
        NullPointerException - if the specified iterable is null or contains a null object.
        See Also:
        Channels.join(Object, Iterable)

      • range

        @NotNull
 @StreamFlow(value=MAP)
public static <N extends Number> Consumer<Channel<N,?>> range(@NotNull
                                                                                               N start,
                                                                                               @NotNull
                                                                                               N end)
        Returns a consumer generating the specified range of data.
        The stream will generate a range of numbers up to and including the end element, by applying a default increment of +1 or -1 depending on the comparison between the first and the last element. That is, if the first element is less than the last, the increment will be +1. On the contrary, if the former is greater than the latter, the increment will be -1.
        Type Parameters:
        N - the number type.
        Parameters:
        start - the first element of the range.
        end - the last element of the range.
        Returns:
        the consumer instance.
